answers.body_markdown:
If you want to test both conditions together, do `a || b`. If you want to test each condition individually, do `if(a) { if (b) { } }`.

For example:

    if (a) {
        if (b) {
            // Both true.
        } else {
            // Only a.
        }
    } else {
        if (b) {
            // Only b.
        } else {
            // Neither true.
        }
    }

Have a look at this

    if(a) {
        if(b) {
           ...
        }
    }

will be equivalent to 

    if(a &amp;&amp; b) {
        ... 
    }

i.e. when `a` is `true`, test `b`, and if it is also `true` run code.

Both codes will have same complexities.  
If you don&#39;t need to do anything after `a` is true then definitely second code will be suitable and vice-versa.

Which one you choose matters when accompanied by an `else`.

In the single `if` case, when you use it with `else`, `else` will run if either `a` or `b` are `false`. However in the case of nested `if`s, `else` will run only if `a` is false, because the program is already in the `if` branch when evaluating `b`.

Here’s an example:

```swift
var a = true
var b = false

// First Case (Single-Line)
if a &amp;&amp; b {
    print(&quot;foo&quot;);
} else {
    print(&quot;bar&quot;);
}
// Output: &quot;bar&quot;

// Second Case (Nested)
if a {
    if b {
        print(&quot;foo&quot;);
    }
} else {
    print(&quot;bar&quot;)
}
// No output

